default9.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is increasing evidence that demand is not currently being met in eye clinics which means people are losing their sight unnecessarily.
default Problems will only increase unless the issue is tackled now. More eye conditions than ever are now treatable and this will increase in the future - coupled with the demands of an aging population eye care capacity must be addressed.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default10.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEye Clinic Liaison Officers (ECLOs) are employees in an eye ward who offer a bridge between health and social care services to people with conditions such as glaucoma or diabetic eye disease. They can: offer information about how to manage the eye conditions, play a role in providing accessible information, signpost patients to appropriate rehabilitation services if they lose a significant amount of sight, talk through treatment options or diagnosis information and prevent patients "falling between the gaps" in the system if hospital appointments are cancelled.
default Secondary care doctors are not equipped with the time or training to confront mental health issues that arise as a consequence of their patient's ill health
default, but ECLOs are able to discuss wellbeing with patients
default.
default 
defaultRNIB recently published a report outlining the critical role that ECLOs play in patient care and this can be accessed at: 
defaulthttp://bit.ly/XcLm8t
default&#xa0;
default10.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLinking low vision services (commonly funded by local authorities and found in a hospital environment) provide aids and rehab services to people with sight loss.
default 
defaultLinking these services with counselling services has a significant impact on patient's independence, physiological outcomes, confidence and ability to socialise.
default default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default11.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople facing a disabling illness are much more likely to face mental health problems as well - especially those with sight loss.
default Yet the majority of people who are registered blind are told there is "nothing more that can be done", discharged from the hospital and left cope on their own.
default Linking low vision services (which provide aids and rehab services) with counselling services has a significant impact on patient's independence, physiological outcomes, confidence and ability to socialise.
default Linking services that already exist is a cost effective way to improve outcomes.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default12.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOlder people are the main users of the NHS and are much more likely than the general population to have sight loss in addition to another condition which will affect its management. Sight loss must be considered in the planning of NHS services if patients are to receive care centred around them.
default 
defaultThere are around two million people in the UK living with sight loss and that number is set to reach four million by 2050. Sight loss predominantly affects older people: one in 30 of the general population are living with sight loss - that figure rises to one in five people aged 75 and one in two people aged 90 and over are living with sight loss.
default 
default 
default13.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSight loss has a massive impact on a person’s ability to manage a long term
default condition
default and itself has a massive impact on health and wellbeing in general.
default 
defaultAs such, sight loss itself should be considered in light of its impact as a co-morbidity 
defaultwhich a
defaultffects long term conditions.
default 
default&#xa0;
default13.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs outlined below
default, people with sight loss
default who use the NHS face multiple barriers in the current system as sight loss is 
defaultoften 
defaultnot 
defaultconsidered or catered to even inside
default the immediate eye care setting:
