default13.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople who have stroke, dementia or a learning disability can often have sight loss which is undiagnosed - which adds further difficulties to their treatment. 
default&#xa0;
default13.3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople who have a stroke are more likely to have sight loss.
default 
default 
defaultHowever
default 
defaultRowe, a leading researcher in the field, noted that currently: Often staff on stroke teams do not refer 
defaultpatients for vision assessment because of a common misperception that little can be done to treat visual impairment following stroke
default&#xa0;
default13.3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople with learning disabilities are ten times more likely to have eye problems than the general population but are less likely to receive timely and appropriate care.
default 
default&#xa0;
default13.3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople with dementia and sight loss face everyday living problems caused by sight loss which are masked by and wrongly attributed to dementia. People with dementia can also develop vision problems as a result of their dementia. 
default750,000 people have dementia in the UK, most of whom are over 65 and around 1 in 7 of the over 65s is living with significant sight loss. By the age of 75 at least 2.5 per cent of people will have both conditions.
default&#xa0;
default13.3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPatient convenience is patchy an
defaultd jeopardises care: see points 8.5.
default 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultAbout two million people have sight loss in the UK. 
defaultPeopl
defaulte can develop sight loss for a n
defaultumber of reasons. Wet Age related macular degeneration affects central vision and about 40,000 people per year develop wet AMD.
default In addition, a further 500,000 people are living with dry type untreatable AMD. 
defaultThis has a massive impact on a person’s general health and wellbeing, for example people with sight loss:
default&#xa0;
